			<p>Oil prices are not only affected by actual non-OPEC production, but also by changes in expectations about future non-OPEC supply. From 2005 through 2008, final production reports for non-OPEC production were consistently lower than forecast expectations. This reduction in anticipated production forced the world to unexpectedly rely more heavily on OPEC crude, drawing down their levels of spare capacity. The downward revisions in expectations of non-OPEC production contributed to upward pressure on oil prices.</p>
